          <chapter>                                                       <!--[0-N]-->								                  <!--[0-1]-->
            <paragraph>By mid-2016, some 500 million people in a quarter of the world economy were living with rates in the red. Unthinkable before the 2008 financial crisis, the idea is to jolt lending, spur inflation and reinvigorate the economy after other options have been exhausted. It’s an unorthodox move that has distorted financial markets and triggered complaints that the strategy is backfiring.</paragraph>
